what is onion architecture


Onion Architecture is a software architectural pattern introduced by Jeffrey Palermo in 2008. Its primary goal is to address the challenges of traditional N-tier architectures—specifically the problem of tight coupling and the "database-centric" mindset.
In Onion Architecture, the Domain (your business logic and entities) is at the absolute center, and dependencies only point inward toward that center.
The Layers of the Onion
 * Domain Entities (The Core):
   This is the heart of the application. It contains the fundamental business objects (e.g., User, Product, Order). These classes have no dependencies on any other layer or framework.
 * Domain Services:
   This layer contains the business logic that involves multiple entities. It defines interfaces (abstractions) for things the application needs to do, but it doesn't implement the technical details.
 * Application Services (Use Cases):
   This layer coordinates the flow of data. It implements the specific "tasks" of your app (e.g., CreateUserAccount). It uses the core entities and domain services to achieve a goal.
 * Infrastructure & User Interface (The Outer Rim):
   This is where the "real world" touches your app. It includes:
   * Databases (SQL, DynamoDB)
   * Web Frameworks (Express, Fastify, Lambda)
   * Third-party APIs (Stripe, Twilio)
   * User Interfaces (React, Vue, CLI)
Key Principles
1. The Dependency Rule
This is the most important rule: Dependencies always point toward the center. * The Inner layers never know anything about the outer layers.
 * The Domain doesn't know if it's being saved in a DynamoDB table or a text file. It doesn't care if the request came from a REST API or a GraphQL query.
2. The Use of Abstractions (Interfaces)
Because the core can't depend on the outer layers, we use Dependency Inversion.
 * The Core defines an interface: IUserRepository.
 * The Infrastructure layer implements that interface: DynamoDbUserRepository.
 * At runtime, the implementation is "injected" into the core.
3. Everything is Pluggable
Because the business logic is isolated, you can swap out the outer layers with minimal effort. You could move from an AWS Lambda environment to a Google Cloud Function, or from PostgreSQL to MongoDB, without changing a single line of your core business logic.
Why use it for Serverless?
In your current AWS Serverless project, Onion Architecture is highly effective because:
 * Testability: You can test your userService.ts (Core) without ever actually connecting to a real DynamoDB.
 * Cleanliness: Your Lambda handlers (Outer Layer) stay very thin, only handling the "plumbing" like HTTP status codes and parsing, while the actual logic stays protected in the center.
Comparison to Traditional Tiered Architecture
| Feature | Traditional N-Tier | Onion Architecture |
|---|---|---|
| Center of Gravity | The Database | The Domain Logic |
| Dependencies | Top-down (UI -> Logic -> DB) | Inward (Outer -> Center) |
| Coupling | Tight (Logic depends on DB) | Loose (Infrastructure depends on Domain) |
| Flexibility | Hard to switch databases | Highly swappable/pluggable |
