To implement Onion Architecture in your aws-serverless-poc, you want to organize your folders so that your business logic (the "Core") is protected from the external "Infrastructure" (AWS, DynamoDB, API Gateway).
1. The Clean Folder Structure
Here is a "Universal List" (万能清淡) for your project structure:
src/
├── core/                 <-- THE INNER ONION (Pure Logic)
│   ├── entities/         <-- Zod Schemas (User, Account)
│   └── use-cases/        <-- Business rules (createUser, deleteUser)
├── infrastructure/       <-- THE OUTER ONION (Tools)
│   ├── persistence/      <-- DynamoDB Client, Repository implementations
│   └── external-apis/    <-- Axios clients for 3rd party services
├── handlers/             <-- THE ENTRY POINT (Lambda)
│   └── user/             <-- createUserHandler.ts (Middy Factory)
└── shared/               <-- Cross-cutting concerns
    └── middleware/       <-- Your restApiHandler factory

2. How the Code Flows (Inward Only)
Layer 1: The Entity (Core)
In src/core/entities/user.ts, you define what a User is using Zod. It doesn't know about AWS.
export const UserSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string(),
  email: z.string().email(),
});
export type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;

Layer 2: The Repository Interface (Core)
In src/core/use-cases/ports.ts, you define what you need from a database, but not how to do it.
export interface UserRepository {
  save(user: User): Promise<void>;
}

Layer 3: The Infrastructure (Outer)
In src/infrastructure/persistence/dynamo-user-repository.ts, you finally use the AWS SDK.
import { docClient } from './client';

export class DynamoUserRepository implements UserRepository {
  async save(user: User) {
    await docClient.put({ TableName: 'users', Item: user });
  }
}

Layer 4: The Handler (Entry Point)
In src/handlers/user/create-user-handler.ts, you use your Middy Factory to glue it all together.
const repo = new DynamoUserRepository();

export const createUserHandler = restApiHandler({
  requestSchema: UserSchema,
}).handler(async (body) => {
  // Logic is decoupled from the HTTP request!
  return await repo.save(body);
});

3. Why this solves your "Requested resource not found"
By separating the Infrastructure (the DynamoDB client) into its own layer, you can easily swap the "Endpoint" based on whether you are running locally or in production.
| Environment | Endpoint | Strategy |
|---|---|---|
| Local (pnpm dev) | http://localhost:8000 | Hits serverless-dynamodb |
| Production | AWS Standard | Hits real DynamoDB |
